    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.17a-17b_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">17a</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead"><hi rend="caps">MRS. JAMES B. PERRY    311 PLEASANT ST.    MEXICO, MISSOURI</hi></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Jan. 14, 1959</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt -</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It has been a great deal of pleasure to follow each session of your television course "Epic America."</p>
                
                <p>Many of the interesting thoughts you have given during your recording will always remain in my memory.</p>
                
                <p>I especially enjoyed the Easter poem you read during the first part of the semester. It was the one you had written for a newspaper publisher. The dedication of "The Song of Three Friends" to Hilda, which was written in Greek, sounded pretty to me; then the lyrics you wrote when you were eighteen, "Let
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.17a-17b_0002"/>    
                
                <fw type="curatorial">17b</fw>
                    
                <fw type="letterhead"><hi rend="caps">MRS. JAMES B. PERRY    311 PLEASANT ST.   MEXICO, MISSOURI</hi></fw>
                    
                    Me Live out My Years" reminded me of William Cullen Bryant's "Thanatopsis." During your lecture on Indian Culture you quoted the prayer Black Elk taught you. I liked it.</p>
                
                <p>Is it too much trouble for you to send me copies of those four pieces of literature? Enclosed you will find a stamped envelope for your convenience.</p>
                
                <p>Thank you for opening new channels of thought for me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Mrs. James B. Perry.</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
